00:10:23.610 --> 00:10:25.460
OK So first off,
Timeline cards.

00:10:25.460 --> 00:10:28.430
Now Timeline cards
can be text.

00:10:28.430 --> 00:10:31.650
It can be images, video.

00:10:31.650 --> 00:10:34.130
It can be rich HTML.

00:10:34.130 --> 00:10:37.170
And they can also be bundles.

00:10:37.170 --> 00:10:40.340
So now you saw, when I was on
the Timeline there, there was

00:10:40.340 --> 00:10:41.020
a single item .

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:41.590
It was an image.

00:10:41.590 --> 00:10:43.480
I tapped on it, and
I got a menu.

00:10:43.480 --> 00:10:46.330
If that item had a page scroll
in the upper right, like this

00:10:46.330 --> 00:10:50.100
Timeline item here, and I tapped
on it, it would open up

00:10:50.100 --> 00:10:51.700
into a sub-timeline.

00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:57.400
This is how you can group
multiple Timeline cards

00:10:57.400 --> 00:11:01.160
together into a single top
level Timeline item.

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:03.700
And this is good for a couple
different things, and I'll

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:05.960
discuss in detail some
best practices here

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:07.120
in the design section.

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:10.010
But you might want to do
pagination with this.

00:11:10.010 --> 00:11:11.270
Or you might want
to do threading.

00:11:11.270 --> 00:11:14.040
For example, if I'm going to
have a conversation over SMS,

00:11:14.040 --> 00:11:17.540
that's going to be in a threaded
bundle with my latest

00:11:17.540 --> 00:11:19.840
message back or forth on top.

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:22.610
I tap in, and I can go through
the whole conversation.

00:11:22.610 --> 00:11:27.070
Or maybe I want to show a little
bit more of a summary

00:11:27.070 --> 00:11:29.210
than just on one
Timeline card.

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:32.420
So I insert a long text string,
and it automatically

00:11:32.420 --> 00:11:33.706
paginates for me.

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:40.390
Now menu items, like the Share
menu item that you saw when I

00:11:40.390 --> 00:11:43.440
tapped on the image, you
can add these yourself.

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:44.590
And they can be of two kinds.

00:11:44.590 --> 00:11:47.210
One, they can be a
system menu item.

00:11:47.210 --> 00:11:48.410
And that you just
have to name.

00:11:48.410 --> 00:11:52.160
And it uses some built-in
functionality of Glass.

00:11:52.160 --> 00:11:53.890
This could be Reply,
Read Aloud.

00:11:53.890 --> 00:11:55.540
These are system menu items.

00:11:55.540 --> 00:11:58.300
Reply will put the user into
voice dictation mode, take

00:11:58.300 --> 00:12:02.330
transcription, send you that
text and the audio file, and

00:12:02.330 --> 00:12:05.020
then you can use that as
you do in your service.

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:08.670
For Read Aloud, Glass will read
aloud to speakable text

00:12:08.670 --> 00:12:11.320
or the text that it finds
on the Timeline item.

00:12:11.320 --> 00:12:14.870
There can also be custom
menu items.

00:12:14.870 --> 00:12:17.990
These are still going to be
simple, quick interactions

00:12:17.990 --> 00:12:18.710
that you build.

00:12:18.710 --> 00:12:21.090
But they can have your name and
your icon, and they can do

00:12:21.090 --> 00:12:23.810
whatever your service
wants them to do.

00:12:27.350 --> 00:12:29.020
Now Shared Contacts.

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:32.110
Shared Contacts can be for
sharing, like I shared to my

00:12:32.110 --> 00:12:34.820
Google+ circle for friends, and
then they see that image

00:12:34.820 --> 00:12:37.880
moments later, or something like
Ice Breaker, which I'm

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:39.520
going to talk about a
little bit later.

00:12:39.520 --> 00:12:41.720
Some of you might have been
playing while you're here at

00:12:41.720 --> 00:12:45.020
Google I/O. Now that's just a
service that takes an image

00:12:45.020 --> 00:12:49.250
and does something different
or interesting with it.

00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:52.510
Now much like the Timeline,
which is a RESTful collection

00:12:52.510 --> 00:12:57.900
that you can insert, update, and
delete items from, Shared

00:12:57.900 --> 00:13:00.550
Contacts is also a collection.

00:13:00.550 --> 00:13:03.490
And typically how you would do
this in the flow of your

00:13:03.490 --> 00:13:06.000
service is the user
would OAuth--

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:07.630
say, hi, I wanted to give
you permissions to

00:13:07.630 --> 00:13:09.140
do stuff for me.

00:13:09.140 --> 00:13:14.270
And then immediately your
service would insert a shared

00:13:14.270 --> 00:13:17.570
contact and subscribe to updates
from that shared

00:13:17.570 --> 00:13:21.180
contact, or anything else the
user does in the Timeline that

00:13:21.180 --> 00:13:24.620
the service wants to
pay attention to.

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:27.710
Now the way those subscriptions
work, again

00:13:27.710 --> 00:13:29.130
another collection.

00:13:29.130 --> 00:13:33.440
You insert a subscription, and
then you start to get updates

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:35.280
on the endpoint that
you specify.

00:13:38.931 --> 00:13:39.410
All right?

00:13:39.410 --> 00:13:43.950
So we have three major
collections so far, Timeline,

00:13:43.950 --> 00:13:48.580
insert cards, add menu items,
Shared Contacts for the

00:13:48.580 --> 00:13:51.600
sharing menu, and
Subscriptions.

00:13:51.600 --> 00:13:54.010
The one last one is Location.

00:13:54.010 --> 00:13:55.850
I'll talk about that
in a moment.

00:13:55.850 --> 00:13:58.000
For Subscriptions, think
of it this way.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:01.710
If you've done pubsubhubbub
before, it's sort of similar.

00:14:01.710 --> 00:14:04.860
You're going to subscribe by
inserting a request into

00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:08.000
Google that creates an item in
the subscription collection.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.630
And then as the user takes
actions covered by that

00:14:11.630 --> 00:14:15.220
subscription, Google will inform
you by calling the

00:14:15.220 --> 00:14:17.440
endpoint that you specify.

00:14:17.440 --> 00:14:20.440
It's a lightweight ping,
so it doesn't take a

00:14:20.440 --> 00:14:21.720
lot of network traffic.

00:14:21.720 --> 00:14:23.870
And most of the time all you
need is that lightweight ping,

00:14:23.870 --> 00:14:25.890
because it includes a
Timeline ID that you

00:14:25.890 --> 00:14:27.980
likely already know.

00:14:27.980 --> 00:14:30.410
But if you want more
information, you can then pull

00:14:30.410 --> 00:14:33.800
that item from the Timeline
item collection.

00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:35.250
Now Location is very similar.

00:14:35.250 --> 00:14:38.270
You can subscribe to Location.

00:14:38.270 --> 00:14:42.400
And then as the user's location
gets updated, you get

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:43.960
a notification.

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:48.740
You pull from the Location
collection to get the actual

00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:51.580
latitude and longitude.

00:14:51.580 --> 00:14:53.110
That make sense?

00:14:53.110 --> 00:14:53.790
All right.

00:14:53.790 --> 00:14:56.480
So that's the platform as we
know it today, the Google

00:14:56.480 --> 00:14:57.730
Mirror API.

00:15:02.570 --> 00:15:04.790
Let's talk a little bit about
what the Google Mirror API is

00:15:04.790 --> 00:15:07.560
good for and some of the use
cases that will feel a little

00:15:07.560 --> 00:15:09.670
bit forced.

00:15:09.670 --> 00:15:13.220
In our conversations about
building stuff on the

00:15:13.220 --> 00:15:16.270
platform, we're always thinking,
as we do around

00:15:16.270 --> 00:15:17.850
Google, what's good
for the user?

00:15:17.850 --> 00:15:21.060
What's going to provide
an excellent Glass

00:15:21.060 --> 00:15:21.920
experience for the user?

00:15:21.920 --> 00:15:25.600
And in those conversations,
about 80% to 90% of the ideas

00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:28.790
we come up with are great Glass
services for the Google

00:15:28.790 --> 00:15:30.060
Mirror API.

00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:34.900
These include being able to send
content to the user and

00:15:34.900 --> 00:15:37.420
microinteractions with that
service, like being able to

00:15:37.420 --> 00:15:43.340
reply, or being able to add an
emoticon to something or +1

00:15:43.340 --> 00:15:48.660
something, and being able to
share out from Glass images

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:52.570
and video, either to be posted
on a social network or for

00:15:52.570 --> 00:15:53.990
your service.

00:15:53.990 --> 00:15:55.860
All those things work
incredibly well

00:15:55.860 --> 00:15:57.290
on the Mirror API.

00:15:57.290 --> 00:16:00.230
You can develop them
very, very quickly.

00:16:00.230 --> 00:16:05.800
But there's a handful of things
that you might want a

00:16:05.800 --> 00:16:09.370
different kind of aspect
to the platform for.

00:16:09.370 --> 00:16:15.130
Those can be when you want your
service to work offline.

00:16:15.130 --> 00:16:18.590
Now if I get updates from "The
New York Times," I can see

00:16:18.590 --> 00:16:20.210
them, even if I don't
have a connection.

00:16:20.210 --> 00:16:22.350
But to actually get those
updates, I needed a connection

00:16:22.350 --> 00:16:24.710
at that time, or to do those
microinteractions.

00:16:24.710 --> 00:16:27.270
Well, what if I have something
like Navigation, as you see

00:16:27.270 --> 00:16:33.220
here, where I want to be able
to interact and get an

00:16:33.220 --> 00:16:36.140
immediate response from Glass?

00:16:36.140 --> 00:16:42.280
Or what if I want to access
hardware features, like the

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:44.160
Location, in real
time on Glass?

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:46.860
Well, for something like that,
you need a native API.

00:16:46.860 --> 00:16:48.720
And that's something we're
working on right now.

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:52.120
It's called the Glass
Development Kit.

00:16:52.120 --> 00:16:54.440
We don't have a lot of details
about this right now, because

00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:56.480
we're actively building it.

00:16:56.480 --> 00:16:58.690
And since we're in the explorer
period and we're

00:16:58.690 --> 00:17:02.600
building it at the same time,
it's actually a really unique

00:17:02.600 --> 00:17:05.010
place for a product to be,
because we're having a

00:17:05.010 --> 00:17:08.099
conversation right now about
what we need to make sure that

00:17:08.099 --> 00:17:12.030
we add to the Glass
Development Kit.

00:17:12.030 --> 00:17:13.720
So my ask do you--

00:17:13.720 --> 00:17:15.680
I make an announcement, and
then I ask you to do

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:17.740
something for me--

00:17:17.740 --> 00:17:20.930
is to tell us, what are your
dreams for Glass that would

00:17:20.930 --> 00:17:23.330
use the Glass Development Kit
but not the Mirror API?

00:17:23.330 --> 00:17:25.958
And what do you want to make
sure we cover in that?

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:31.430
Later in the day, if you go to
the hack your Glass session,

00:17:31.430 --> 00:17:34.900
HY and PY might talk a little
bit more about the GDK.

00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:36.410
And we might talk about
in the Fireside Chat.

00:17:36.410 --> 00:17:38.720
And of course, if you want to
come up and ask me later, we

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:40.020
can talk about it
in more depth.

00:17:40.020 --> 00:17:41.320
And I'll take questions
at the end.

00:17:45.820 --> 00:17:47.320
All right.

00:17:47.320 --> 00:17:48.400
So we've talked about
platform.

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:50.240
We've talked about the Google
Mirror API, which is what you

00:17:50.240 --> 00:17:53.240
build with today to get services
to users and play

00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:56.460
with the Glass experience and
really understand the design

00:17:56.460 --> 00:17:57.805
and user experience of Glass.

00:17:57.805 --> 00:18:00.115
And we've talked a little bit
about the GDK that'll be

00:18:00.115 --> 00:18:03.410
coming some time in the future,
where you'll be able

00:18:03.410 --> 00:18:06.915
to do things like offline and
immediate access to hardware.

00:18:09.780 --> 00:18:15.050
The user experience, this big
next section of my talk, is

00:18:15.050 --> 00:18:16.340
about design.

00:18:16.340 --> 00:18:19.510
It's about how do you make an
excellent Glass service for

00:18:19.510 --> 00:18:20.990
the user, not just
technically?

00:18:20.990 --> 00:18:22.700
But what are the paradigms
that you use?

00:18:22.700 --> 00:18:24.630
What are the user patterns
that you use?

00:18:24.630 --> 00:18:27.630
And to start with, we have four
guidelines that you've

00:18:27.630 --> 00:18:29.280
heard me speak about before--

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:32.440
I've covered these in more depth
elsewhere, but I want to

00:18:32.440 --> 00:18:34.890
touch on them, because they
really add context to all of

00:18:34.890 --> 00:18:37.610
the other items that
talk about today--

00:18:37.610 --> 00:18:41.752
the first of which is
to design for Glass.

00:18:41.752 --> 00:18:44.940
And this is really key, and
there's a remarkable amount of

00:18:44.940 --> 00:18:46.190
depth in here.

00:18:46.190 --> 00:18:48.900
Because at the top level, you
don't want to take an

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:50.930
experience on mobile or
on the web and just

00:18:50.930 --> 00:18:51.870
stamp it out on Glass.

00:18:51.870 --> 00:18:54.050
It's not going to work,
because Glass is

00:18:54.050 --> 00:18:56.340
fundamentally different.

00:18:56.340 --> 00:18:58.350
And the one essential
thing that you must

00:18:58.350 --> 00:19:00.760
do is test on Glass.

00:19:00.760 --> 00:19:03.520
Use Glass in your daily life.

00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:06.740
Add your service, and use your
service in your daily life,

00:19:06.740 --> 00:19:08.200
and then you're really
going to know what

00:19:08.200 --> 00:19:11.420
works and what doesn't.

00:19:11.420 --> 00:19:17.160
The second big thing here
is don't get in the way.

00:19:17.160 --> 00:19:19.700
Remember I talked about what are
the things that are good

00:19:19.700 --> 00:19:22.710
for a Glass user.

00:19:22.710 --> 00:19:24.480
Well, getting in the
way is not good.

00:19:24.480 --> 00:19:26.300
Getting in the way takes them
out of their life and puts a

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:28.500
barrier between them and
what they're doing.

00:19:28.500 --> 00:19:30.050
And that's not what we're
doing with Glass.

00:19:30.050 --> 00:19:35.760
We want your service to
improve their life.

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:38.980
And sort of a corollary here is
that you never would want

00:19:38.980 --> 00:19:41.490
to take precedence over
the user's experience.

00:19:41.490 --> 00:19:43.280
So you would never want to send
them a notification that

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:46.460
if they didn't respond would
degrade their experience with

00:19:46.460 --> 00:19:48.710
your service.

00:19:48.710 --> 00:19:51.580
They should be able to ignore
notifications, and your

00:19:51.580 --> 00:19:54.960
service keeps chugging along,
giving them what they want

00:19:54.960 --> 00:19:57.700
when they need it.

00:19:57.700 --> 00:19:59.060
Keep it timely.

00:19:59.060 --> 00:20:02.560
Glass is a very now device.

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:04.810
Your phone, you might do stuff
over the last week.

00:20:04.810 --> 00:20:08.070
Look at your calendar
four days from now.

00:20:08.070 --> 00:20:10.030
Your laptop, you've got data
on there from the last few

00:20:10.030 --> 00:20:11.370
months or year.

00:20:11.370 --> 00:20:15.030
But Glass is really about what
are you doing right now.

00:20:15.030 --> 00:20:16.690
And when you think about that
your service, you want to

00:20:16.690 --> 00:20:19.820
deliver content to the user
that's important to them at

00:20:19.820 --> 00:20:21.070
that moment.

00:20:25.260 --> 00:20:26.440
And then one last one.

00:20:26.440 --> 00:20:29.740
Avoid the unexpected, especially
the unexpected and

00:20:29.740 --> 00:20:30.530
the unpleasant.

00:20:30.530 --> 00:20:32.940
And this is bad on
any platform.

00:20:32.940 --> 00:20:36.210
But it's particularly dangerous
on Glass when the

00:20:36.210 --> 00:20:38.210
experience is so intimate
to the user.

00:20:38.210 --> 00:20:41.390
They're wearing your
experience.

00:20:41.390 --> 00:20:46.230
So you really need to respect
that relationship, and don't

00:20:46.230 --> 00:20:47.760
do anything unexpected.

00:20:47.760 --> 00:20:51.190
Just Be honest about the
intention of your application,

00:20:51.190 --> 00:20:53.070
about your Glassware.

00:20:53.070 --> 00:20:56.950
And give them preferences to be
able to get notifications

00:20:56.950 --> 00:20:59.430
maybe during certain times or
know how many they're going to

00:20:59.430 --> 00:21:02.026
get before they sign up.

00:21:02.026 --> 00:21:02.510
All right.

00:21:02.510 --> 00:21:03.530
So those are our four
guidelines.

00:21:03.530 --> 00:21:04.910
And those are things that
you can kind just

00:21:04.910 --> 00:21:06.070
stick in your pocket.

00:21:06.070 --> 00:21:07.460
And when you look at your Glass
service and you have a

00:21:07.460 --> 00:21:10.320
question, is this going to be
right for the user, you can

00:21:10.320 --> 00:21:14.140
measure it against those four
things really easily.

00:21:14.140 --> 00:21:18.110
And we've talked about those
before, but since that time

00:21:18.110 --> 00:21:20.530
we've been spending more and
more time with our partners.

00:21:20.530 --> 00:21:23.460
And we've gotten a lot of little
lessons as well, a lot

00:21:23.460 --> 00:21:25.610
of user patterns that work
really well and a lot of

00:21:25.610 --> 00:21:28.900
learnings around the different
paradigms in Glass that I'd

00:21:28.900 --> 00:21:30.150
like to share with you.

00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:34.590
So here are the types
of Timeline cards

00:21:34.590 --> 00:21:36.170
that you might use.

00:21:36.170 --> 00:21:43.830
You've got text, HTML templates,
images, and video.

00:21:43.830 --> 00:21:47.440
I'm going to touch on some
notes for each of these.

00:21:47.440 --> 00:21:49.790
Now we also document these on
our documentation, and we'll

00:21:49.790 --> 00:21:52.930
continue to expand these best
practices, these tips and

00:21:52.930 --> 00:21:56.310
tricks, as we move forward and
as we learn together in this

00:21:56.310 --> 00:21:58.770
explorer period.

00:21:58.770 --> 00:22:03.810
First off, if you're only
sending text, just send text.

00:22:03.810 --> 00:22:05.450
Don't use an HTML template.

00:22:05.450 --> 00:22:08.370
And the cool thing here is that
if the text is too long

00:22:08.370 --> 00:22:09.720
for one Timeline item.

00:22:09.720 --> 00:22:10.970
it's going to autopaginate.

00:22:13.230 --> 00:22:16.900
So a user can tap on that
Timeline item, and there'll be

00:22:16.900 --> 00:22:19.390
a Read More menu item, and
they'll be able to swipe

00:22:19.390 --> 00:22:21.020
through that text.

00:22:21.020 --> 00:22:23.100
If what you're sending to the
user is text, this is the

00:22:23.100 --> 00:22:25.190
easiest and quickest and
most powerful way

00:22:25.190 --> 00:22:27.890
to get that to them.

00:22:27.890 --> 00:22:29.450
And it looks a little
bit like this.

00:22:29.450 --> 00:22:31.750
Again, you'll see that text,
tap on it, get to the Read

00:22:31.750 --> 00:22:33.750
More, and you can swipe through
multiple pages of

00:22:33.750 --> 00:22:36.930
text, in this case,
the dramatically

00:22:36.930 --> 00:22:38.180
interesting Lorem Ipsum.

00:22:41.230 --> 00:22:41.930
OK.

00:22:41.930 --> 00:22:42.650
HTML.

00:22:42.650 --> 00:22:47.540
Now this is when you once more
rich or flexible designs.

00:22:47.540 --> 00:22:49.970
And maybe you want to combine
both text and

00:22:49.970 --> 00:22:52.420
images on one item.

00:22:52.420 --> 00:22:54.740
Now HTML is a little bit
tricky on Glass.

00:22:54.740 --> 00:22:56.260
You really need to
test on Glass.

00:22:56.260 --> 00:22:58.520
And we do have a great tool
called the Developer

00:22:58.520 --> 00:22:59.840
Playground.

00:22:59.840 --> 00:23:01.240
It's got the CSS built in.

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:04.000
You can edit HTML inline and
see it right there the web

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:08.140
browser and hit send and have
it go straight to Glass.

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:09.010
That's really helpful.

00:23:09.010 --> 00:23:10.960
And we also have these
templates.

00:23:10.960 --> 00:23:12.980
We've taken some time just like,
OK, what are some of the

00:23:12.980 --> 00:23:16.630
big categories of usage
for Timeline items?

00:23:16.630 --> 00:23:20.710
We've provided these templates
for you to go in and edit and

00:23:20.710 --> 00:23:21.960
make your own.

00:23:24.450 --> 00:23:27.350
However, if you want to break
past those templates and do

00:23:27.350 --> 00:23:30.430
something a little bit more
stylized and specific, you can

00:23:30.430 --> 00:23:33.890
also add a style tag inline
with the HTML.

00:23:33.890 --> 00:23:35.425
Now it won't do JavaScript.

00:23:35.425 --> 00:23:38.130
But you can add your
own CSS, your own

00:23:38.130 --> 00:23:40.310
custom IDs and classes.

00:23:40.310 --> 00:23:43.020
Just remember to always
test on Glass.

00:23:43.020 --> 00:23:45.460
Start with the Playground, and
keep sending those to Glass to

00:23:45.460 --> 00:23:47.780
make sure it renders the
way you want it.

00:23:47.780 --> 00:23:50.950
And also, if you use custom
HTML, make sure that as we

00:23:50.950 --> 00:23:53.910
upgrade the system software on
Glass that you keep testing

00:23:53.910 --> 00:23:55.450
that to make sure
nothing changes.

00:23:58.060 --> 00:24:02.600
We have a couple UI grid
templates here to get you

00:24:02.600 --> 00:24:05.650
thinking about what's the
padding and the spacing that

00:24:05.650 --> 00:24:08.420
will make your Glassware
consistent with the rest of

00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:11.140
the Class UI so that it's
familiar and easy

00:24:11.140 --> 00:24:12.390
to use for the users.

00:24:20.890 --> 00:24:22.510
Photos and video attachment.

00:24:22.510 --> 00:24:24.110
There's a couple best
practices in here.

00:24:24.110 --> 00:24:30.750
First, it's 16 by 9, and the
resolution is 640 by 360.

00:24:30.750 --> 00:24:34.450
You want to use that resolution,
if you can.

00:24:34.450 --> 00:24:37.960
And the reason is it's going to
transfer to Glass faster,

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:41.590
and it'll be the perfect size
for showing full screen.

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:43.260
It doesn't need to be
resized on Glass.

00:24:43.260 --> 00:24:45.790
It's going to look
as you intended.

00:24:45.790 --> 00:24:48.190
And for videos, they
should be short.

00:24:48.190 --> 00:24:49.140
This is for two reasons.

00:24:49.140 --> 00:24:51.030
One, you're sending it to
Glass over the air.

00:24:51.030 --> 00:24:54.970
It's going to use the user's
data connection.

00:24:54.970 --> 00:24:57.900
But another reason is that,
again, we don't want Glass to

00:24:57.900 --> 00:25:01.950
get in the way of the
user and their life.

00:25:01.950 --> 00:25:05.040
So getting a video and looking
for 30 seconds or maybe up to

00:25:05.040 --> 00:25:07.000
a minute makes sense.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.440
I can take that pause when I'm
walking between meetings, and

00:25:09.440 --> 00:25:11.180
that can be really magical
experience.

00:25:11.180 --> 00:25:13.630
But if you push me 30 minutes
of video, I'm never going to

00:25:13.630 --> 00:25:15.060
watch it, for one.

00:25:15.060 --> 00:25:16.360
And it's going to be
distracting and

00:25:16.360 --> 00:25:17.510
confusing to the user.

00:25:17.510 --> 00:25:18.960
It's about short interactions.

00:25:18.960 --> 00:25:20.420
It's not about staring
up all day.

00:25:20.420 --> 00:25:21.670
It's about living your life.

00:25:24.680 --> 00:25:27.080
And another thing that I'd
like to announce today--

00:25:27.080 --> 00:25:29.210
this will be available in
the documentation soon--

00:25:29.210 --> 00:25:31.390
is video streaming.

00:25:31.390 --> 00:25:34.230
So what you know about the
Mirror API so far is that if

00:25:34.230 --> 00:25:36.610
you want to upload an image or
a video, you add it as an

00:25:36.610 --> 00:25:39.700
attachment to a Timeline item
that you insert into the

00:25:39.700 --> 00:25:41.700
Timeline collection.

00:25:41.700 --> 00:25:43.300
You do this once
for every user.

00:25:43.300 --> 00:25:46.030
So if you have 1,000 users and
you want one video to go to

00:25:46.030 --> 00:25:49.500
all of them, you upload that
video 1,000 times.

00:25:49.500 --> 00:25:52.350
It makes more sense to do that
for the video intended for

00:25:52.350 --> 00:25:54.740
that user specifically
and update to

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:56.600
them from your service.

00:25:56.600 --> 00:25:59.040
If you're going to broadcast
things to users, what makes

00:25:59.040 --> 00:26:01.700
the most sense is to
do video streaming.

00:26:01.700 --> 00:26:03.900
Now we're going to add some more
details about video types

00:26:03.900 --> 00:26:06.000
and quality in our
documentation, and that's best

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:07.290
place to reference it.

00:26:07.290 --> 00:26:10.190
But you so you know how this
works is this is a URL

00:26:10.190 --> 00:26:11.810
attachment.

00:26:11.810 --> 00:26:15.190
So when you insert the Timeline
item into the user's

00:26:15.190 --> 00:26:19.470
Timeline collection, instead
of adding a multi-part

00:26:19.470 --> 00:26:23.470
attachment with the video
content inline, you can add

00:26:23.470 --> 00:26:25.050
just a URL.

00:26:25.050 --> 00:26:26.950
And then Google's going
to handle the rest.

00:26:26.950 --> 00:26:28.200
That's pretty cool, right?

00:26:31.090 --> 00:26:33.670
Everybody's who's been inserting
