00:26:36.721 --> 00:26:37.260
All right.

00:26:37.260 --> 00:26:38.830
Let's talk about bundling.

00:26:38.830 --> 00:26:40.990
Bundling is super powerful
but tricky.

00:26:44.310 --> 00:26:46.640
There's a few tips I can give
you to do this right so it's

00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:48.610
going to be really obvious to
the user and it's going to

00:26:48.610 --> 00:26:51.100
make a lot of sense to them.

00:26:51.100 --> 00:26:55.260
First off, there's many
kinds of bundles.

00:26:55.260 --> 00:26:57.760
There's single item bundles,
and there's

00:26:57.760 --> 00:26:58.860
multiple item bundles.

00:26:58.860 --> 00:27:00.200
Now what do I mean by that?

00:27:00.200 --> 00:27:02.900
A single item bundle is where
you insert a single Timeline

00:27:02.900 --> 00:27:09.280
item, you specify the HTML
attribute as the cover card,

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:12.250
and then HTML pages is
an array of strings.

00:27:12.250 --> 00:27:13.780
They're your subsequent
pages when the user

00:27:13.780 --> 00:27:15.030
taps into the bundle.

00:27:15.030 --> 00:27:18.490
This is a single Timeline item,
so it should logically

00:27:18.490 --> 00:27:21.410
be a single item with
multiple pages.

00:27:21.410 --> 00:27:23.850
That's really straightforward,
right?

00:27:23.850 --> 00:27:27.150
The multiple item one, this
could be for threading, or it

00:27:27.150 --> 00:27:28.230
could be a collection.

00:27:28.230 --> 00:27:30.290
There's a couple great
examples of this.

00:27:30.290 --> 00:27:32.380
You've seen "The New York
Times" on Glass.

00:27:32.380 --> 00:27:35.960
That's a bundle of the latest
top headlines from "The New

00:27:35.960 --> 00:27:39.358
York Times" for the last hour.

00:27:39.358 --> 00:27:42.900
You tap into it, and you'll
see those multiple items.

00:27:42.900 --> 00:27:45.790
Threading is something like
SMS or messaging back and

00:27:45.790 --> 00:27:47.040
forth in a service.

00:27:50.140 --> 00:27:52.540
All you need to do is insert
additional items.

00:27:52.540 --> 00:27:54.660
You set the bundle ID.

00:27:54.660 --> 00:27:57.180
In the case of "The New York
Times", the way they insert

00:27:57.180 --> 00:27:59.000
them will constitute
the order.

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:01.340
In the case of threading, you
don't even worry about that,

00:28:01.340 --> 00:28:06.220
because the latest items are
always going to appear on top.

00:28:06.220 --> 00:28:08.300
Now a trick for all of these
things, especially the

00:28:08.300 --> 00:28:12.700
multiple item bundles, is
to have a digest cover.

00:28:12.700 --> 00:28:15.550
This is a cover not where you
say what's in the bundle but

00:28:15.550 --> 00:28:17.380
you show the user what's
in the bundle.

00:28:17.380 --> 00:28:19.390
And "The New York Times" does
a great job of this.

00:28:19.390 --> 00:28:24.470
You'll see this digest cover has
images for a number of the

00:28:24.470 --> 00:28:25.720
headlines contained within.

00:28:30.570 --> 00:28:33.730
Menu items, a couple short
notes about this.

00:28:33.730 --> 00:28:37.100
Menu items are one line, and
there's just a few characters.

00:28:37.100 --> 00:28:41.270
This is on purpose, because
they're short and actionable.

00:28:41.270 --> 00:28:44.410
I can easily scan through a good
menu and choose what I

00:28:44.410 --> 00:28:46.920
want in just a few moments.

00:28:46.920 --> 00:28:50.010
That means that not only is it
really easy to recognize what

00:28:50.010 --> 00:28:52.590
this menu item does, because
it's clear in one or two short

00:28:52.590 --> 00:28:56.430
words, but there's also a
handful of menu items, not

00:28:56.430 --> 00:28:59.470
more than that.

00:28:59.470 --> 00:29:02.050
Always make sure to
specify an icon.

00:29:02.050 --> 00:29:07.200
And be careful with Dismiss
and Delete.

00:29:07.200 --> 00:29:10.090
These are similar, but they're
a little different.

00:29:10.090 --> 00:29:12.310
Most the time you're not
going to want Dismiss.

00:29:12.310 --> 00:29:14.030
It doesn't make a lot
of sense on Glass.

00:29:14.030 --> 00:29:17.140
Because the way the Timeline
works, for those of you that

00:29:17.140 --> 00:29:22.010
have Glass, is you know
when updates come in

00:29:22.010 --> 00:29:23.280
and time moves on.

00:29:23.280 --> 00:29:25.830
You just don't go all the
way back on Timeline.

00:29:25.830 --> 00:29:28.410
It just kind of decays
over time.

00:29:28.410 --> 00:29:31.270
You're only looking at
your recent stuff.

00:29:31.270 --> 00:29:34.620
So they sort of automatically
dismiss, in a way.

00:29:34.620 --> 00:29:36.700
So you wouldn't want to get
the user in the habit of

00:29:36.700 --> 00:29:39.360
having to just dismiss, unless
you wanted to give them the

00:29:39.360 --> 00:29:41.810
option, like I don't want to
see this on my Timeline Or

00:29:41.810 --> 00:29:45.750
maybe that's an indication to
your service of what kinds of

00:29:45.750 --> 00:29:48.400
updates they like or
they don't like.

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:51.080
Delete, on the other hand, when
you do this it shouldn't

00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:55.180
just remove it from the
user's Glass Timeline.

00:29:55.180 --> 00:29:58.280
It should also delete that
item on your service.

00:29:58.280 --> 00:30:00.640
A great example of this is
when I share an image to

00:30:00.640 --> 00:30:02.465
Google+ and there's
that Delete Item.

00:30:02.465 --> 00:30:03.550
I tap that Delete Item.

00:30:03.550 --> 00:30:06.750
It deletes it from my Glass
Timeline, and it deletes the

00:30:06.750 --> 00:30:08.180
post on Google+.

00:30:08.180 --> 00:30:10.520
It's very clear to the
user what it does.

00:30:14.020 --> 00:30:14.160
OK.

00:30:14.160 --> 00:30:16.090
Let's talk about Shared
Contacts.

00:30:16.090 --> 00:30:17.190
A couple notes here.

00:30:17.190 --> 00:30:20.350
Make sure that when you insert
a shared contact that the

00:30:20.350 --> 00:30:23.360
image that you use
is 640 by 360.

00:30:23.360 --> 00:30:26.590
That way, if it's the one, it'll
show full screen and

00:30:26.590 --> 00:30:29.000
it'll be beautiful.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:32.620
Make sure to always specify
acceptTypes.

00:30:32.620 --> 00:30:35.830
Now these are MIME types that
say what your shared contact

00:30:35.830 --> 00:30:36.940
can be used for.

00:30:36.940 --> 00:30:41.980
So maybe you do image slash
asterisk, in which case any

00:30:41.980 --> 00:30:46.700
images that the user finds and
they tap on that image and the

00:30:46.700 --> 00:30:49.130
Share menu, your shared
contact will show up.

00:30:49.130 --> 00:30:52.510
Maybe you also want
to do video.

00:30:52.510 --> 00:30:55.390
Now when the user does share
items on your service, we have

00:30:55.390 --> 00:30:58.100
two things that people have
started to use which make a

00:30:58.100 --> 00:31:02.810
lot of sense, #throughglass
and Sent through Glass.

00:31:02.810 --> 00:31:05.610
So with your service, it makes
sense to include a hashtag,

00:31:05.610 --> 00:31:07.110
like it's a post on
your service.

00:31:07.110 --> 00:31:10.515
Adding #throughglass is a great
way to have a through

00:31:10.515 --> 00:31:12.160
line of what that user
is sharing while

00:31:12.160 --> 00:31:14.930
on the go from Glass.

00:31:14.930 --> 00:31:17.000
If you're doing messaging,
however, where maybe it

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:19.930
doesn't make sense to have a
hashtag, but you still want to

00:31:19.930 --> 00:31:22.540
indicate to somebody that
somebody was saying this while

00:31:22.540 --> 00:31:25.660
they were walking between
meetings, then Sent through

00:31:25.660 --> 00:31:28.240
Glass makes a lot of sense
there, just to append at the

00:31:28.240 --> 00:31:30.670
end of the message.

00:31:30.670 --> 00:31:33.520
Add these, and there'll be a lot
more clarity, as messages

00:31:33.520 --> 00:31:36.290
are going to go through
and similar

00:31:36.290 --> 00:31:37.540
to the other Glassware.

